# Day 1: Create a Python Virtual Environment for ML

The xFusionCorp Industries data science team needs a standardised Python environment for their new ML project. Set up a virtual environment with the required ML libraries on the controlplane host.
Create a Python virtual environment named ml-env under /root/code/ using python3 -m venv.
Activate the environment and install the following packages: numpy, pandas, scikit-learn, and matplotlib.
Generate a requirements.txt file using pip freeze and save it at /root/code/requirements.txt.

o set up the standardized Python environment for the xFusionCorp Industries data science team, follow these steps on the controlplane host.

## 1. Create the Virtual Environment
First, ensure the directory exists and then create the ml-env virtual environment.

Bash
mkdir -p /root/code/
python3 -m venv /root/code/ml-env

## 2. Activate and Install Packages
Activate the environment to ensure the libraries are installed within the isolated container rather than the system Python.

Bash
## Activate the environment
source /root/code/ml-env/bin/activate

## Upgrade pip (recommended for stability)
pip install --upgrade pip

## Install the required ML libraries
pip install numpy pandas scikit-learn matplotlib

##3. Generate requirements.txt
Finally, use pip freeze to capture the specific versions of the installed packages and save the output to the requested location.

## Bash
pip freeze > /root/code/requirements.txt

## Verification
To verify the setup, you can check that the file exists and contains the expected libraries:

Check file existence: ls -l /root/code/requirements.txt

Check file content: grep -E "numpy|pandas|scikit-learn|matplotlib" /root/code/requirements.txt

## Deactivate: Once finished, you can exit the environment by simply typing deactivate.
